1
00:01:27,667 --> 00:01:30,261
We couldn't see a thing.
As usual.

2
00:01:42,549 --> 00:01:45,040
I hurried.
I wanted to see you.

3
00:01:46,653 --> 00:01:47,677
Here.

4
00:01:48,188 --> 00:01:49,985
I picked these for you.

5
00:01:51,324 --> 00:01:52,689
They smell nice.

6
00:01:54,194 --> 00:01:55,456
Camille...

7
00:01:55,695 --> 00:01:58,459
You don't look well.
You're ever so pale.

8
00:02:01,101 --> 00:02:04,229
Are you eating enough?
Are you sleeping enough?

9
00:02:06,273 --> 00:02:08,264
You've been up the hill again.

10
00:02:10,477 --> 00:02:11,444
The front...

11
00:02:11,978 --> 00:02:14,071
Do you know how far away it is?

12
00:02:15,348 --> 00:02:18,442
Do you really think
you'll see something?

13
00:02:20,454 --> 00:02:22,046
You're all so stupid!

14
00:02:24,825 --> 00:02:28,226
I'm sick
of your sentimental superstitions.

15
00:02:28,728 --> 00:02:30,889
Do they get in that state for you?

16
00:02:31,031 --> 00:02:33,499
I bet they're glad without women!

17
00:02:33,667 --> 00:02:35,897
- You'll see when...
- When I'm married?

18
00:02:36,336 --> 00:02:40,272
I won't spend my time
waiting for my husband.

19
00:02:40,407 --> 00:02:42,341
I'll follow him whatever!

20
00:02:44,244 --> 00:02:45,336
Has the postman been?

21
00:02:51,485 --> 00:02:53,043
He had nothing for you.

22
00:02:53,587 --> 00:02:55,612
François can't write every day.

23
00:03:00,694 --> 00:03:03,390
He's all you care about anyway.

24
00:03:06,099 --> 00:03:08,590
You were different
before you married.

25
00:03:11,638 --> 00:03:12,764
Here!

26
00:03:16,676 --> 00:03:19,543
Frankly, you don't deserve it.

27
00:03:32,592 --> 00:03:34,856
"Post Code 313.

28
00:03:35,829 --> 00:03:37,888
"May 15, 1917.

29
00:03:38,031 --> 00:03:41,364
"Camille, I don't want you
to write back to me.

30
00:03:41,501 --> 00:03:43,526
"You'll never see me again.

31
00:03:45,372 --> 00:03:46,566
"François."

32
00:04:16,036 --> 00:04:17,401
Where are you going?

33
00:04:20,140 --> 00:04:21,835
I'm leaving home.

34
00:04:28,648 --> 00:04:30,206
Go home, madam.

35
00:04:31,217 --> 00:04:33,811
A woman shouldn't be out alone.

36
00:04:34,921 --> 00:04:35,717
I have to go.

37
00:04:35,855 --> 00:04:37,914
Don't be a nuisance. Go home!

38
00:08:37,564 --> 00:08:38,690
Who are you?

39
00:08:40,200 --> 00:08:42,031
What are you doing here?

40
00:08:42,168 --> 00:08:45,501
I was lost.
I spotted you so I came over.

41
00:08:50,076 --> 00:08:53,045
Who are you? Where are you from?

42
00:08:53,179 --> 00:08:55,670
Verneuil. I've walked a long time.

43
00:08:57,317 --> 00:08:59,649
- How old are you?
- Seventeen.

44
00:09:01,454 --> 00:09:02,352
No whiskers yet.

45
00:09:05,959 --> 00:09:07,392
Where are you going?

46
00:09:07,660 --> 00:09:08,649
To fight the war.

47
00:09:09,195 --> 00:09:10,685
You're too young.

48
00:09:10,830 --> 00:09:15,290
Get lost. Don't waste my time.
Go back where you came from.

49
00:09:48,501 --> 00:09:50,128
Who goes there?

50
00:09:53,773 --> 00:09:55,138
Who goes there?

51
00:10:36,983 --> 00:10:39,451
Anyone not on our side
is an enemy.

52
00:10:41,154 --> 00:10:42,621
You should have said.

53
00:10:43,990 --> 00:10:46,185
I'm not your enemy, I'm with you.

54
00:10:48,127 --> 00:10:49,651
You bloody fool.

55
00:10:50,763 --> 00:10:52,822
You could have been killed.

56
00:10:53,366 --> 00:10:55,197
No, impossible.

57
00:11:03,977 --> 00:11:06,912
No other wounds?
You've examined him?

58
00:11:07,046 --> 00:11:07,910
There's no need.

59
00:11:08,047 --> 00:11:09,639
Whatever you say.

60
00:11:10,883 --> 00:11:12,783
We'll get rid of him tomorrow.

61
00:11:12,919 --> 00:11:15,683
He won't be better by tomorrow, sir.

62
00:11:31,771 --> 00:11:33,238
Go to sleep, lad.

63
00:11:34,640 --> 00:11:37,370
My name's not "lad",
my name's Camille.

64
00:11:38,311 --> 00:11:41,212
Pour the batter
on the Montmorency cherries.

65
00:11:41,347 --> 00:11:44,373
A real clafoutis
needs Montmorency cherries.

66
00:11:44,517 --> 00:11:45,609
At the orphanage...

67
00:11:45,752 --> 00:11:48,448
Shut up. You're a thief.

68
00:11:48,588 --> 00:11:50,988
Even your rifle
was stolen from a German.

69
00:11:55,461 --> 00:11:57,395
When you wake up,

70
00:11:57,530 --> 00:12:01,523
the aroma of clafoutis
straight from the oven...

71
00:12:02,001 --> 00:12:03,025
is magical.

72
00:12:04,370 --> 00:12:05,837
Got any family?

73
00:12:07,774 --> 00:12:09,708
No, nobody.

74
00:12:10,176 --> 00:12:11,973
Nobody? Nobody at all?

75
00:12:12,111 --> 00:12:13,874
No, I'm alone in the world.

76
00:12:14,013 --> 00:12:16,072
Incredible, you're just like me.

77
00:12:16,215 --> 00:12:18,308
I don't have anybody either.

78
00:12:18,918 --> 00:12:20,351
They have family.

79
00:12:20,486 --> 00:12:21,885
Where are you from?

80
00:12:22,021 --> 00:12:23,545
None of your business.

81
00:12:23,689 --> 00:12:26,123
No one wants to know where I'm from?

82
00:12:26,259 --> 00:12:28,250
Antoine, where are you from?

83
00:12:28,394 --> 00:12:31,192
"Atlantis, that land beneath the sea

84
00:12:31,330 --> 00:12:33,730
"where giant squid swim gracefully,

85
00:12:36,102 --> 00:12:39,594
"where mermaids let down their hair

86
00:12:39,739 --> 00:12:41,832
"while waiting for lost sailors,

87
00:12:41,974 --> 00:12:44,169
"where the sun's rays nev..."

88
00:12:45,812 --> 00:12:47,006
How does it go?

89
00:12:47,146 --> 00:12:49,478
"...never reach people's eyes,

90
00:12:49,615 --> 00:12:51,640
"no more than their heartbeats."

91
00:12:52,518 --> 00:12:53,917
What a load of rubbish.

92
00:12:54,053 --> 00:12:55,918
What are you talking about?

93
00:12:56,055 --> 00:12:58,819
We don't want to talk anyway,
so shut up.

94
00:13:00,560 --> 00:13:01,788
Talk...

95
00:13:02,662 --> 00:13:04,061
Talk...

96
00:13:07,333 --> 00:13:10,268
I'm like you.
I won't make any more efforts.

97
00:13:11,938 --> 00:13:13,030
I'm sick of it.

98
00:14:37,723 --> 00:14:39,020
Philippe...

99
00:14:40,293 --> 00:14:41,590
No.

100
00:14:44,931 --> 00:14:46,262
Get up!

101
00:14:47,633 --> 00:14:48,964
Philippe!

102
00:14:58,811 --> 00:14:59,800
Lieutenant...

103
00:14:59,946 --> 00:15:02,005
It's nearly over.

104
00:15:02,148 --> 00:15:03,945
You'll be able to rest soon.

105
00:15:05,017 --> 00:15:07,508
Don't think about it.
It's over now.

106
00:15:08,821 --> 00:15:11,346
You're not alone. We're here.

107
00:15:14,327 --> 00:15:16,056
What are you staring at?

108
00:15:17,430 --> 00:15:19,523
You've never had a nightmare?

109
00:15:20,366 --> 00:15:22,129
Go back to sleep.

110
00:15:31,911 --> 00:15:34,277
The lieutenant knows what he's doing.

111
00:15:34,413 --> 00:15:37,439
I have the feeling we left from here,

112
00:15:37,583 --> 00:15:39,050
we're here now...

113
00:15:39,185 --> 00:15:41,380
and that we have all this left.

114
00:15:41,520 --> 00:15:43,385
At least.

115
00:15:43,589 --> 00:15:46,615
If we left from there,
we're not here now.

116
00:15:46,759 --> 00:15:48,624
I reckon we're here instead.

117
00:15:48,761 --> 00:15:50,251
We headed to the left?

118
00:15:50,896 --> 00:15:53,228
We made a detour at one point.

119
00:15:54,634 --> 00:15:57,262
It's like a tiny forest.

120
00:15:57,403 --> 00:15:58,131
It's funny.

121
00:15:58,271 --> 00:15:59,932
A fir tree...

122
00:16:00,773 --> 00:16:02,206
A birch.

123
00:16:04,744 --> 00:16:07,872
We'd need to crawl through it.
Like ants.

124
00:16:08,014 --> 00:16:09,276
Like ants...

125
00:16:13,519 --> 00:16:14,645
What's going on?

126
00:16:14,787 --> 00:16:17,722
We're meeting La Douce.
We can't miss her.

127
00:16:18,824 --> 00:16:19,813
A woman?

128
00:16:19,959 --> 00:16:22,723
Yeah, a very beautiful woman,

129
00:16:22,862 --> 00:16:24,853
old, cold but that's okay.

130
00:16:25,498 --> 00:16:27,329
Why are you meeting her?

131
00:16:28,067 --> 00:16:30,092
You ask a lot of questions.

132
00:16:30,236 --> 00:16:31,760
She'll help us.

133
00:16:31,904 --> 00:16:33,064
To do what?

134
00:16:33,205 --> 00:16:35,639
To find our way.
Give it a rest now!

135
00:16:59,031 --> 00:17:01,522
That's north, that's south.

136
00:17:01,667 --> 00:17:03,532
I thought we'd never make it.

137
00:17:03,669 --> 00:17:05,933
I expected it to be a lot bigger.

138
00:17:08,240 --> 00:17:09,798
So where's La Douce?

139
00:17:09,942 --> 00:17:11,034
In front of you.

140
00:17:11,177 --> 00:17:13,008
Old, cold, showing the way.

141
00:17:13,145 --> 00:17:15,136
But you stop here, Camille.

142
00:17:15,815 --> 00:17:19,546
If you head upstream,
you'll reach a village in an hour.

143
00:17:19,685 --> 00:17:21,312
They'll look after you.

144
00:17:23,622 --> 00:17:25,317
Which way are you going?

145
00:17:34,967 --> 00:17:36,400
I'm coming too.

146
00:17:36,535 --> 00:17:37,559
No.

147
00:18:08,067 --> 00:18:08,761
Fetch him.

148
00:18:49,108 --> 00:18:50,336
All right...

149
00:18:52,111 --> 00:18:53,635
Where were we?

150
00:18:54,814 --> 00:18:56,281
Chapter two.

151
00:18:56,882 --> 00:18:58,850
Remember what had happened?

152
00:18:58,984 --> 00:19:00,315
They were under the sea.

153
00:19:00,453 --> 00:19:01,420
That's right.

154
00:19:01,754 --> 00:19:04,086
"Atlantis opened her arms to them."

155
00:19:04,390 --> 00:19:08,417
I don't get it.
Is Atlantis a woman or a country?

156
00:19:09,795 --> 00:19:13,128
It's a "wonderful land".
We already told you that.

157
00:19:14,099 --> 00:19:15,657
"Atlantis opened her arms...

158
00:19:16,836 --> 00:19:18,929
"The depths were deep blue,

159
00:19:19,071 --> 00:19:21,596
"'so blue, it made your head spin.

160
00:19:28,180 --> 00:19:31,809
"It was cool,
cooler than on land but very mild.

161
00:19:31,951 --> 00:19:34,579
"They would never know
bad weather again.

162
00:19:34,720 --> 00:19:36,654
"'This climate didn't...

163
00:19:39,859 --> 00:19:42,123
"prevent the fauna and flora
from developing freely.

164
00:19:42,261 --> 00:19:45,697
"Even the insects
were of prodigious dimensions."

165
00:19:46,265 --> 00:19:48,324
No, that's not the right tone.

166
00:19:54,607 --> 00:19:59,374
"They were struck dumb
by this fabulous discovery..."

167
00:20:10,189 --> 00:20:12,089
I've seen Atlantis.

168
00:20:14,660 --> 00:20:16,355
You're not dead then?

169
00:20:17,396 --> 00:20:19,296
You've seen Atlantis?

170
00:20:20,599 --> 00:20:24,626
Yes, it was beautiful.
But I've forgotten everything.

171
00:20:24,770 --> 00:20:27,136
You don't know what you're saying.

172
00:20:27,940 --> 00:20:30,568
Keep reading.
You're not in Atlantis yet.

173
00:20:30,709 --> 00:20:32,404
You don't look like us.

174
00:20:32,545 --> 00:20:34,945
Wear these to be like a soldier.

175
00:20:48,294 --> 00:20:51,263
The cadet will rob anyone,
especially corpses.

176
00:20:51,397 --> 00:20:53,592
You'll smell of death even more now.

177
00:21:38,811 --> 00:21:40,108
You should have stayed at home.

178
00:21:41,580 --> 00:21:42,706
I want to fight.

179
00:21:42,881 --> 00:21:44,678
I hate childishness.

180
00:21:45,618 --> 00:21:47,279
It won't work with me.

181
00:21:49,555 --> 00:21:51,921
I know why you're clinging to us.

182
00:21:55,794 --> 00:21:58,262
You don't look like you want to live.

183
00:21:59,465 --> 00:22:01,330
You look like someone...

184
00:22:02,401 --> 00:22:03,925
who's known hardship.

185
00:22:05,904 --> 00:22:06,871
A lot of it.

186
00:22:08,307 --> 00:22:10,707
You're clinging to us
so you can die?

187
00:22:11,710 --> 00:22:13,109
No, not at all.

188
00:22:15,614 --> 00:22:18,811
You're looking for something.
I don't know what.

189
00:22:19,752 --> 00:22:21,549
I can't worry about that.

190
00:22:22,388 --> 00:22:24,856
I want to get my men out alive.

191
00:22:25,624 --> 00:22:28,354
I won't put them at risk, understand?

192
00:22:29,328 --> 00:22:33,526
I'll hand you over to the authorities
once we reach the front.

193
00:22:34,199 --> 00:22:36,394
They punish boys who want to fight?

194
00:22:36,535 --> 00:22:39,095
I won't let you set a bad example

195
00:22:39,772 --> 00:22:42,741
or give ideas to my men,
dumb ideas.

196
00:22:44,243 --> 00:22:46,211
I don't have any bad ideas.

197
00:22:47,980 --> 00:22:50,175
You don't know yourself then?

198
00:23:04,029 --> 00:23:06,497
Since I can't get rid of you,
do me a favour.

199
00:23:06,632 --> 00:23:07,929
Leave them be.

200
00:23:08,667 --> 00:23:09,964
Don't bother them.

201
00:23:11,336 --> 00:23:13,133
They need to stay focused.

202
00:23:58,250 --> 00:24:00,377
I, the blind girl

203
00:24:01,720 --> 00:24:04,917
It may be the influence
of the seasons

204
00:24:05,057 --> 00:24:08,117
But I can tell I'm back in France

205
00:24:08,293 --> 00:24:10,693
I slept badly last night

206
00:24:12,064 --> 00:24:15,761
I dreamt of England
I was expecting

207
00:24:15,901 --> 00:24:19,428
The last child of a little lord

208
00:24:22,674 --> 00:24:27,839
He was caressing me
Saying things I didn't understand

209
00:24:29,348 --> 00:24:32,078
I wish I could have known

210
00:24:32,217 --> 00:24:35,209
The colour of his eyes

211
00:24:36,188 --> 00:24:38,588
But I don't speak English

212
00:24:38,757 --> 00:24:42,158
He held me captive, I swear

213
00:24:43,228 --> 00:24:44,627
In his bedchamber

214
00:24:44,763 --> 00:24:48,722
There were long drapes everywhere

215
00:24:54,173 --> 00:24:57,574
The little lord

216
00:24:57,709 --> 00:25:04,581
Came to me every night, I swear

217
00:25:06,451 --> 00:25:09,614
In his bedchamber

218
00:25:09,755 --> 00:25:13,213
I beg you

219
00:25:13,592 --> 00:25:16,493
I must continue my journey now

220
00:25:22,568 --> 00:25:27,972
He was caressing me
Saying things I didn't understand

221
00:25:29,441 --> 00:25:32,308
I wish I could have known

222
00:25:32,444 --> 00:25:35,641
The colour of his eyes

223
00:25:36,515 --> 00:25:38,676
But I don't speak English

224
00:25:38,817 --> 00:25:42,719
He held me captive, I swear

225
00:25:43,522 --> 00:25:44,921
In his bedchamber

226
00:25:45,057 --> 00:25:49,619
There were long drapes everywhere

227
00:25:54,333 --> 00:25:57,530
It may be
the influence of the seasons

228
00:25:57,669 --> 00:25:59,500
But I must say farewell

229
00:25:59,638 --> 00:26:00,696
To the little lord

230
00:26:00,839 --> 00:26:04,741
If I needed him

231
00:26:04,877 --> 00:26:07,243
Would he come to me?

232
00:26:11,917 --> 00:26:14,750
Would he come to me?

233
00:26:18,824 --> 00:26:21,952
Would he come to me?

234
00:27:17,449 --> 00:27:18,848
What's this?

235
00:27:18,984 --> 00:27:22,112
French soldiers who died in battle.

236
00:27:47,045 --> 00:27:49,775
Camille, it's not good
to stay here too long.

237
00:27:54,987 --> 00:27:56,614
And that one?

238
00:27:56,755 --> 00:27:58,188
A German soldier.

239
00:28:33,959 --> 00:28:35,586
You know how to cook?

240
00:28:36,361 --> 00:28:37,293
A little.

241
00:28:39,064 --> 00:28:41,555
Only one man here does a fine job.

242
00:28:41,700 --> 00:28:44,260
Antoine's a schoolteacher.

243
00:28:44,436 --> 00:28:46,529
Do you clout your pupils?

244
00:28:46,705 --> 00:28:48,570
Are you crazy? Look at him.

245
00:28:48,707 --> 00:28:51,005
He's the soul of kindness.

246
00:28:51,143 --> 00:28:52,804
His pupils all get top marks.

247
00:28:52,978 --> 00:28:55,139
My teacher used to belt me.

248
00:28:55,313 --> 00:28:57,178
You were rude to her?

249
00:28:57,315 --> 00:28:59,442
No, but I was slow.

250
00:28:59,618 --> 00:29:01,142
I held the others back.

251
00:29:02,187 --> 00:29:03,620
Like us now.

252
00:29:19,337 --> 00:29:21,498
Did you like school, Frédéric?

253
00:29:26,611 --> 00:29:27,771
It's ready.

254
00:29:40,358 --> 00:29:42,087
You seem calm tonight.

255
00:29:45,263 --> 00:29:46,423
Young Camille...

256
00:29:51,369 --> 00:29:52,836
I'm not hungry.

257
00:29:52,971 --> 00:29:54,768
I'll get more wood.

258
00:30:27,472 --> 00:30:29,269
What are you doing here?

259
00:30:30,642 --> 00:30:32,769
We're heading up to the front.

260
00:30:33,345 --> 00:30:34,004
And the others?

261
00:30:39,451 --> 00:30:41,885
Gone for food. They'll be back soon.

262
00:30:43,922 --> 00:30:44,650
Who are you?

263
00:30:45,223 --> 00:30:47,783
Georges Guibert, liaison officer.

264
00:30:47,959 --> 00:30:50,393
I'm Camille. Camille Robin.

265
00:30:51,897 --> 00:30:54,161
Can I ask you something, Georges?

266
00:30:54,666 --> 00:30:56,133
Go ahead.

267
00:31:00,338 --> 00:31:01,862
Any news of the 30th?

268
00:31:02,040 --> 00:31:04,372
I can't give out that information.

269
00:31:04,509 --> 00:31:07,603
Who do you think I am? The postman?

270
00:31:07,746 --> 00:31:09,873
I need to know.

271
00:31:10,015 --> 00:31:12,176
You're not allowed to know.

272
00:31:16,087 --> 00:31:19,250
Here, this was a present.
I'm very fond of it.

273
00:31:21,226 --> 00:31:22,955
I don't care if you are.

274
00:31:25,130 --> 00:31:26,688
Is it worth much?

275
00:31:26,831 --> 00:31:28,196
Yes, it's gold.

276
00:31:33,905 --> 00:31:35,395
The news isn't good.

277
00:31:36,208 --> 00:31:37,402
Meaning?

278
00:31:42,247 --> 00:31:44,647
With the dead and the prisoners...

279
00:31:45,717 --> 00:31:47,617
that regiment's nearly gone.

280
00:31:48,954 --> 00:31:50,945
Where are the prisoners?

281
00:31:52,290 --> 00:31:53,723
No idea.

282
00:31:55,327 --> 00:31:57,261
I have to go now.

283
00:31:58,029 --> 00:31:59,394
You fooled me.

284
00:32:00,332 --> 00:32:01,924
This isn't worth much.

285
00:32:26,958 --> 00:32:29,017
I thought he'd never leave.

286
00:32:29,160 --> 00:32:30,855
You're a talkative one.

287
00:32:31,496 --> 00:32:33,794
He was just a liaison officer.

288
00:32:33,932 --> 00:32:35,399
Why were you up there?

289
00:32:35,533 --> 00:32:38,093
No reason. A false alarm.

290
00:32:43,975 --> 00:32:45,772
Lieutenant!

291
00:32:46,745 --> 00:32:49,578
Is it true
what he said about the 30th?

292
00:32:59,090 --> 00:33:00,751
You think we're stupid?

293
00:33:01,893 --> 00:33:04,361
Who was that soldier earlier?

294
00:33:05,730 --> 00:33:08,164
Why these questions about the 30th?

295
00:33:10,635 --> 00:33:12,626
We weren't born yesterday.

296
00:33:12,771 --> 00:33:14,898
We spot them right away.

297
00:33:16,374 --> 00:33:18,137
What are you talking about?

298
00:33:18,276 --> 00:33:21,109
About guys who follow soldiers,

299
00:33:21,246 --> 00:33:23,476
who pretend to be with us,

300
00:33:23,615 --> 00:33:25,515
who are there when we need them,

301
00:33:25,650 --> 00:33:28,016
then tell the Germans everything.

302
00:33:29,921 --> 00:33:31,218
I'm not a spy.

303
00:34:05,457 --> 00:34:06,890
The bastard!

304
00:34:14,833 --> 00:34:17,427
No time to look for him.
Let's get going.

305
00:36:50,755 --> 00:36:53,986
I was unfair with you.
It can't be helped.

306
00:36:56,127 --> 00:36:58,027
I'm sticking with you anyway.

307
00:37:01,065 --> 00:37:02,589
You're wrong.

308
00:37:05,003 --> 00:37:06,800
You're a stranger among us.

309
00:37:07,839 --> 00:37:10,706
Whatever you do,
you'll stay a stranger.

310
00:37:11,876 --> 00:37:13,776
Not anymore, I think.

311
00:37:16,347 --> 00:37:18,110
You're different.

312
00:37:18,249 --> 00:37:20,080
I know that.

313
00:37:22,587 --> 00:37:24,384
And don't ask me why.

314
00:38:11,202 --> 00:38:13,796
I, the blind girl

315
00:38:14,505 --> 00:38:18,805
I wasn't seeking favours, only work

316
00:38:18,943 --> 00:38:24,813
I left at seventeen for Italy

317
00:38:27,051 --> 00:38:32,148
Tell your prophets to pray for me

318
00:38:34,659 --> 00:38:39,119
For I am still unemployed

319
00:38:41,866 --> 00:38:47,771
I met a man from Turin
at the age of twenty

320
00:38:49,574 --> 00:38:52,543
Some things are beautiful

321
00:38:57,782 --> 00:39:02,242
For the things that men have made

322
00:39:05,423 --> 00:39:09,917
Live on throughout the years

323
00:39:30,281 --> 00:39:34,479
But work has no meaning

324
00:39:37,989 --> 00:39:42,085
Unless it absorbs you completely

325
00:39:47,065 --> 00:39:49,966
Are you asleep, my brother?

326
00:39:54,739 --> 00:39:57,503
You who have stayed on the front

327
00:39:57,642 --> 00:39:59,405
Listen to this

328
00:40:02,980 --> 00:40:07,178
Listen to this, little brother

329
00:40:07,985 --> 00:40:10,977
If I needed him

330
00:40:11,122 --> 00:40:15,559
Would he come to me?

331
00:40:16,794 --> 00:40:21,424
Would he come to me?

332
00:40:22,667 --> 00:40:27,195
Would he come to me?

333
00:40:31,142 --> 00:40:32,268
Lieutenant Paulhan,

334
00:40:32,410 --> 00:40:35,208
80th infantry regiment,
12th company.

335
00:40:35,847 --> 00:40:37,337
And the others?

336
00:40:37,482 --> 00:40:38,847
Private Marin,

337
00:40:39,617 --> 00:40:42,211
Private Briançon, Private Périnelle,

338
00:40:42,920 --> 00:40:44,683
Private Cohen,

339
00:40:44,822 --> 00:40:47,757
Private Ménicourt,
Private Lamouroux and the others.

340
00:40:49,227 --> 00:40:50,854
What are you doing out?

341
00:40:50,995 --> 00:40:53,122
We're joining the 26th regiment.

342
00:40:55,767 --> 00:40:57,496
Go on. I'll make my report.

343
00:40:57,635 --> 00:41:00,229
What's that uniform?

344
00:41:00,371 --> 00:41:01,804
His clothes were stolen.

345
00:41:01,939 --> 00:41:05,272
We'll see the quartermaster
to get him new ones.

346
00:41:49,187 --> 00:41:50,654
We'll stop here.

347
00:41:51,489 --> 00:41:54,652
The front is a mile or so that way.

348
00:41:56,894 --> 00:41:57,918
All right...

349
00:41:58,863 --> 00:42:00,330
The branch there.

350
00:42:01,866 --> 00:42:03,493
The trunk there.

351
00:42:04,502 --> 00:42:05,491
Move it!

352
