404
00:46:42,146 --> 00:46:43,545
He says none of it...

405
00:46:44,949 --> 00:46:46,473
is any use.

406
00:50:12,923 --> 00:50:15,050
What are you doing?

407
00:50:20,798 --> 00:50:22,026
We're not soldiers now.

408
00:50:22,333 --> 00:50:24,267
What do you mean?

409
00:50:25,369 --> 00:50:26,563
Because of Philippe.

410
00:50:26,970 --> 00:50:28,870
- He doesn't exist!
- Watch it!

411
00:50:29,006 --> 00:50:30,473
Calm down.

412
00:50:36,246 --> 00:50:40,114
We'd been together since
January 1916. We were very close.

413
00:50:40,684 --> 00:50:43,881
Then, one day last April,

414
00:50:44,822 --> 00:50:47,689
we were ordered to attack once again.

415
00:50:48,759 --> 00:50:51,523
It was April 20.
I'll always remember.

416
00:50:52,663 --> 00:50:55,632
I saw Philippe
turn as white as a sheet.

417
00:50:55,766 --> 00:50:57,666
I'd never seen him like that.

418
00:50:58,268 --> 00:50:59,826
He stood up.

419
00:51:00,838 --> 00:51:04,205
He started to speak,
saying he didn't want to go.

420
00:51:06,243 --> 00:51:08,336
I tried to reason with him.

421
00:51:09,580 --> 00:51:11,445
I didn't want him punished.

422
00:51:11,582 --> 00:51:13,812
I didn't want his record hurt.

423
00:51:15,986 --> 00:51:18,079
So I swore to him

424
00:51:18,222 --> 00:51:20,656
that he would be like before.

425
00:51:22,493 --> 00:51:23,858
Just like before...

426
00:52:03,534 --> 00:52:05,434
We ran off along the pipe.

427
00:52:07,671 --> 00:52:10,265
Then I heard him cry out.

428
00:52:11,108 --> 00:52:14,271
I heard Philippe cry out,
"Lieutenant!"

429
00:52:14,912 --> 00:52:16,345
I turned for a second

430
00:52:16,480 --> 00:52:19,472
and I saw him
on the ground behind us.

431
00:52:19,616 --> 00:52:21,811
The German fire started raking us.

432
00:52:23,220 --> 00:52:25,279
They had made it in too.

433
00:52:27,958 --> 00:52:29,391
We had no choice.

434
00:52:32,029 --> 00:52:33,428
What did you do?

435
00:52:33,597 --> 00:52:36,794
The only thing we could do.
We left Philippe there

436
00:52:36,934 --> 00:52:38,731
and we ran,

437
00:52:38,869 --> 00:52:40,700
ran as fast as we could.

438
00:52:42,606 --> 00:52:43,595
And then?

439
00:52:47,478 --> 00:52:49,173
Then...

440
00:52:50,447 --> 00:52:52,278
we went back,

441
00:52:52,416 --> 00:52:54,509
had leave and never returned.

442
00:52:54,651 --> 00:52:55,811
And we're alive.

443
00:52:59,490 --> 00:53:00,650
And now?

444
00:53:02,025 --> 00:53:03,652
We're deserters!

445
00:53:29,987 --> 00:53:32,217
It's the only spot on the river.

446
00:53:32,356 --> 00:53:34,654
Once we cross, we'll be in Belgium.

447
00:53:39,663 --> 00:53:41,392
La Douce is just back there.

448
00:53:42,266 --> 00:53:44,257
That bastard will give the alert.

449
00:53:58,315 --> 00:53:59,475
Camille!

450
00:55:17,027 --> 00:55:18,858
What does this gesture mean?

451
00:55:19,963 --> 00:55:22,158
It means he had three children.

452
00:55:36,880 --> 00:55:38,438
Where did you get that?

453
00:55:38,649 --> 00:55:41,277
There's a farm nearby.
I helped myself.

454
00:55:41,685 --> 00:55:43,585
I never taught you to pilfer.

455
00:55:44,254 --> 00:55:46,051
You're putting us at risk,

456
00:55:46,623 --> 00:55:48,250
you thieving idiot.

457
00:55:49,593 --> 00:55:51,458
What do I do? Take them back?

458
00:55:55,132 --> 00:55:57,965
Here, eat.

459
00:55:58,101 --> 00:56:00,069
You can't let yourself starve.

460
00:56:09,613 --> 00:56:11,843
We mean bad luck now anyway.

461
00:56:14,851 --> 00:56:17,843
We weren't ashamed of you before
but now...

462
00:56:19,956 --> 00:56:22,584
You can never tell your fiancée this.

463
00:56:22,726 --> 00:56:24,660
You'll have a secret.

464
00:56:24,828 --> 00:56:26,557
I don't know where she is.

465
00:56:28,832 --> 00:56:30,459
You don't know?

466
00:56:33,136 --> 00:56:34,262
No.

467
00:56:35,472 --> 00:56:37,372
She's a long way from home.

468
00:56:37,874 --> 00:56:39,466
I don't know where she is.

469
